{{Infobox military conflict | conflict = | width = | partof = | image = | caption = | date = | place = [[Salaga]], Ghana | coordinates = 8°33′N 0°31′W | map_type = | map_relief = | latitude = | longitude = | map_size = | map_marksize = | map_caption = | map_label = | territory = | result = | status = | combatants_header = | combatant1 = | combatant2 = | combatant3 = | commander1 = | commander2 = | commander3 = | units1 = | units2 = | units3 = | strength1 = | strength2 = | strength3 = | casualties1 = | casualties2 = | casualties3 = | notes = | campaignbox =
}}The '''1892 Sack of Salaga''' was a [[Gonja people|Gonja]] civil war for the control of the town of [[Salaga]] that occurred on December 5, 1892. A rebellion led by [[Kabachewura Isifa]] and assisted by his Dagomba and Nanumba allies overthrew [[Kpembewura Napo]] who died in exile in the same year.
[[List of rulers of the Northern state of Dagomba|Yaa Naa]] Andani, overload of Dagbon at that time was against the disruption in the region, and sent a strongly worded letter to the incumbent [[Kpembewura Isanwurfo]] in 1894 to quell the internecine struggles to avoid further hurting trade in the slave market.<ref name="google">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=6sYAre7Z12UC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=sack+of+salaga&source=bl&ots=zJDZH53tum&sig=yWpw25XPe6q40Zi99jbQ3NZxaOI&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivlbaIr6rKAhXLuRQKHV-oDJwQ6AEIKzAD#v=onepage&q=sack%20of%20salaga&f=false | title=Contesting Islam: "Homegrown Wahhabism," Education and Muslim Identity in Northern Ghana, 1920--2005 | publisher=ProQuest | author=Abdulai Iddrisu | year=2009 | location=University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign | pages=283 | isbn=9781109220643}}</ref> The war led to a mass exodus of mostly [[Zongo settlements|Zongo people]] out of the region, significantly depleting its population and giving birth to a wave of Islamic proselytizing in the forest areas of modern Ghana.<ref name="Africa">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=YPK5oEz4X28C&pg=PA601&lpg=PA601&dq=sack+of+salaga&source=bl&ots=B3OZA6klCW&sig=kInzs6M7yIU9iCUlbqO7bXi0V40&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivlbaIr6rKAhXLuRQKHV-oDJwQ6AEILjAE#v=onepage&q=sack%20of%20salaga&f=false | title=Arabic Literature of Africa, Volume 4: The Writings of Western Sudanic Africa | publisher=BRILL | author=John O. Hunwick, R. Rex S. O'Fahey | year=2003 | pages=814 | isbn=9789004124448}}</ref>
