{{Freemasonry}}
The '''Grand Orient of the Netherlands''' or '''Grand East of the Netherlands''' ([[Dutch language|Dutch]]: ''Orde van Vrijmetselaren onder het Grootoosten der Nederlanden'') is a [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] [[Grand Lodge]] in the Netherlands.  It falls within the mainstream Anglo-American tradition of Freemasonry, being recognized by The [[United Grand Lodge of England]]<ref>[http://www.ugle.org.uk/provinces/olodges/euro.htm Foreign Grand Lodges Recognised by The United Grand Lodge of England - Europe] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040221181010/http://www.ugle.org.uk/provinces/olodges/euro.htm |date=2004-02-21 }}  Accessed 10 August 2008</ref> and the 51 Grand Lodges in the United States.  In addition to its jurisdiction over nine districts<ref>http://www.vrijmetselarij.nl/Organisatie/Regios/tabid/619/Default.aspx</ref> in the Netherlands, it also administers three Lodges in Suriname through the Provincial Grand Lodge of Suriname,<ref name="vrijmetselarij.nl">http://www.vrijmetselarij.nl/Organisatie/Provincialegrootloges/tabid/593/Default.aspx</ref> three lodges in [[Curaçao]], one in [[South Africa]], one in [[Thailand]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vrijmetselarij.nl/Organisatie/Regios/BuitenNederland/tabid/1189/Default.aspx?regio=BN |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081025154438/http://www.vrijmetselarij.nl/Organisatie/Regios/BuitenNederland/tabid/1189/Default.aspx?regio=BN |archivedate=2008-10-25 |df= }}</ref> and through the Provincial Grand Lodge of the Caribbean, three lodges in Aruba and one in St. Maarten.<ref name="vrijmetselarij.nl"/>  In the Netherlands it claims to have 145 lodges with 5,792 members.<ref name="stichtingargus.nl">[http://www.stichtingargus.nl/vrijmetselarij/ovo_en.html Orde van Vrijmetselaren onder het Grootoosten der Nederlanden], English language version</ref>

It also runs the Prince Frederick Museum, and has an online catalog available for its library.

It was founded in either 1756<ref name="stichtingargus.nl"/> or 1757<ref>[http://www.freemasons-freemasonry.com/europe_grand_lodges.html The Builder magazine], 1924</ref>

==Historic Grand Lodges under the Grand Orient==

The Grand Orient of the Netherlands used to have provincial Grand Lodges under its jurisdiction, including the Grand Lodge of South Africa and the Grand Lodge of the Transvaal.<ref>Africa, [https://books.google.com/books?id=lU5e-E6wBeEC&pg=PA37&lpg=PA37&ots=v1fwrlJIsa&dq=Grand+orient+of+the+Netherlands page 37], Encyclopedia of Freemasonry, Part 1 By Albert G. Mackey</ref>  One of the Lodges that was subservient to the Grand Lodge hosted the early legislative assemblies of the [[Cape Colony]].<ref>[http://www.andrewcusack.com/2009/11/03/die-parlementsgebou/ The Houses of Parliament, Cape Town], Andrew Cusack</ref>  

Active [[Freemasonry in Indonesia|freemasonry]] existed throughout the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now: [[Indonesia]]). In 1922 a Dutch Provincial Grand Lodge, under the Grand Orient of the Netherlands, at Weltevreden ([[Jakarta|Batavia]]) controlled twenty Lodges in the colony: fourteen in [[Java]], three in [[Sumatra]] and others in [[Makassar]] and [[Salatiga]].<ref>[http://www.phoenixmasonry.org/mackeys_encyclopedia/j.htm Mackey's Encyclopedia of Freemasonry]</ref>

Administers the Provincial Grand Lodge of Zimbabwe which has 5 lodges under its jurisdiction, 3 in Harare and one each in Marondera and Bulawayo.  The Grand Lodge was formed in 1963 and the first lodge, Zambesia  in Bulawayo in 1896.

